node.text: @pearlynkmin yea for a while i felt that way too... but i started to realise how difficult it was for them to find words to express themselves and also the discomfort they feel in their bodies when they get angry.. that rage within.. or feelings of upset.. i suppose its a fine line too and parents know best if its showing emotions because they want to get what they want or if they are genuinely upset about a situation... amen to learning more and I love reading ur posts and insights ❤️

Having these two at home with me involves lots of laughter, mess, chaos, screams and fighting. Looking back at all these pictures from home is one that is such a blessing in disguise. One I’ll probably never trade with. ⁣
⁣
What was my Mother’s Day gift you ask me, I’ll say it was re-connecting with Rey. She’s always had a problem expressing herself and her feelings. Her meltdowns were un stoppable and we used to send her to timeout thinking that was the best solution. ⁣
⁣
Not saying it’s not the correct way but we definitely didn’t use it in the right way. The last couple of weeks I’ve adopted a new method learning from this book I was reading “no-drama discipline” which was getting to her level to calm her down, knowledge her feelings and to HTHT with her. Took us a long time with lots of patience and grace but I’m finally seeing the light at the end of the tunnel. ⁣
⁣
Now she comes up to me to tell me how she’s feeling whether it’s feeling sad or happy. It’s soo much easier to talk to her with so much lesser meltdowns! ⁣
⁣
Incredibly amazed and thankful at the same time. Jude is on another level, going through his terrible twos which I’ve yet to figure him out. ⁣
⁣
I can’t stressed how important these moments of meltdowns are in parenting, so much more than the activities I do with them or what I cook for them. These are the most important moments where you get to shape and define them, teach them to respond and not react. These are lifelong skills they’ll never be able to learn elsewhere. ⁣

Being a present parent I think it not so much about the quantity of time you spend with them, but how you respond in these exact crucial moments, the best lessons for our kids. ⁣
⁣

@jboonette it is! Took me a long while to understand coz to me it’s like “giving in” and spoiling the child. So much to learn babe!! Yes amen to that I hope we never stop trying to learn and understand as parents. ❤️❤️😘

@pearlynkmin yea for a while i felt that way too... but i started to realise how difficult it was for them to find words to express themselves and also the discomfort they feel in their bodies when they get angry.. that rage within.. or feelings of upset.. i suppose its a fine line too and parents know best if its showing emotions because they want to get what they want or if they are genuinely upset about a situation... amen to learning more and I love reading ur posts and insights ❤️

Yes!!! No drama discipline is an amazing book and resource ;) glad that the connection with you and rey has strengthened! ❤️ meltdowns are important because kids feel a lot and they show us how they feel through their behavior, bodies and meltdowns. It can feel super tense for adults and counterintuitive to hug and hold them when they are trashing and angry but its one of the most powerful tools both for parent and child. Recently when olivia meltdown for whatever reason, I just stand there with her and then I tell her to let me know when she's ready for a hug. And quite often she just comes and hugs me and standing there just listening to her racing breath slow down and heart beat calm down... no words is just so powerful and healing... so many everyday lessons and I feel like we never stop learning too as parents! 🙌 beautiful and honest sharing as always!!!
@plueonigiri it’s not heavy so I used stick on hooks!
